3.2 FUNCTIONAL REQUIREMENTS 
3.2.1 USE CASE DIAGRAMS
The system manages interactions between the Student and the Administrator within a secured system boundary.
•	STUDENT USE CASES
1.	Preference Submission: Mandatory ranking of all subjects (1 to n). Includes automated checks for full ranking and program eligibility.
2.	Result Access: Viewing the final allotment with an optional download of the allotment letter.
•	ADMINISTRATOR USE CASES
1.	Data Management: Importing student (CGPA), subject (seats/baskets), and preference data.
2.	System Validation: Mandatory verification of CGPAs, roll numbers, and duplicate rankings.
3.	Allocation Control: Triggering the two-phase engine (OC Allotment followed by Multi-Pass Elective Allotment).
4.	Reporting: Generating vacancy summaries and final allocation lists.
3.2.2 USE CASE SPECIFICATIONS
The system logic follows a strict multi-phase workflow:
1.	Phase 1 & 2 (Validation): Ensures data integrity and correct program-subject mapping.
2.	Phase 3 (Merit Sorting): Sorts students by CGPA (descending) with Roll Number as a tie-breaker.
3.	Phase 4 (OC Allotment): Mandatory subjects are assigned immediately with no seat limits; the associated basket is then locked.
4.	Phase 5 (Elective Allotment): A multi-pass process assigns the highest available preference based on seat capacity and basket restrictions until quotas are met.
3.2.3 ANALYSIS CLASSES
These classes define the core information stored and processed by the system:
1.	Student: StudentID, Name, Roll No, Program, CGPA.
2.	Subject: SubjectID, Name, Basket ID, Capacity, Course Type (OC/Elective).
3.	Preference: StudentID, SubjectID, Priority Rank (1 to n).
4.	Allotment: StudentID, SubjectID, Allocation Status.
3.2.4 DATA FLOW DIAGRAMS (DFDs)
•	 INFORMATION FLOW (DFD LEVEL 0 & 1)
LEVEL 0:
The Student provides preferences, and the Admin provides subject data and rules to the system, which returns results and reports.
LEVEL 1:
Data is validated, stored, and then passed through sequential processes:
"Sort by CGPA" → "Allocate OC Subjects" → "Allocate Electives" → "Generate Reports".
•	 PROCESS DESCRIPTION
1. STUDENT:
Must include credential verification, ranking validation, and program mapping checks.
2. ADMINISTRATOR:
Triggers validation (CGPA, duplicates, mapping) before initiating the two-phase allocation.
•	DATA DICTIONARY
1.	Student Data: Student ID, Name, Roll Number, Program, CGPA.
2.	Subject Data: Subject ID, Name, Basket ID, Seat Capacity, Course Type.
3.	Preference Data: Student ID, Subject ID, Priority (1 to n).

3.3 LOGICAL DATABASE REQUIREMENTS
•	The system shall maintain separate relational tables for:
•	Student Records
•	Subject Repository
•	Preference Store
•	Allocation Results
•	Primary and foreign key constraints shall ensure data integrity.

3.4 PERFORMANCE REQUIREMENTS
•	The allocation engine shall process the entire batch within acceptable institutional time limits.
•	System shall support concurrent student access during preference submission window.

3.5 DESIGN CONSTRAINTS
o	One Subject Per Basket: The system must strictly prevent multiple allocations from the same Basket ID.
o	OC Priority: OC subjects must be allotted immediately upon selection, bypassing all seat capacity checks.
•	Merit Order: The allocation engine must strictly process students in descending order of CGPA.

3.6 SOFTWARE SYSTEM ATTRIBUTES
3.6.1 SECURITY
•	Role-based authentication (Student/Admin)
•	Protection of sensitive CGPA data
•	No unauthorized modifications
3.6.2 RELIABILITY
•	Same input data must always produce identical allocation output.
3.6.3 AVAILABILITY
•	High availability during preference and reporting phases.
3.6.4 MAINTAINABILITY
•	Modular architecture (Validation, Merit, OC, Elective, Reporting modules).
3.6.5 PORTABILITY
•	Platform independent; compatible with standard web browsers.

